WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Something I go on about all the time is how we take the present for granted when it is

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.080
[Amit Varma]: so, so contingent. Take India, for example. We think of India as a fixed geographical

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:22.880
[Amit Varma]: entity, almost as something inevitable, something meant to be, and now as something permanent.

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:29.240
[Amit Varma]: But we are a recent nation, born out of circumstance and happenstance, maintained perhaps by inertia.

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:35.000
[Amit Varma]: When India gained independence in 1947, this India that we now inhabit was anything but

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: inevitable. In fact, at times it must have seemed so unlikely. It wasn't just a question

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:45.600
[Amit Varma]: of holding British India together after splitting it in two. There were almost 600 princely

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:50.500
[Amit Varma]: states, all with their own agreements with the British, many of whom wanted to join neither

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:55.400
[Amit Varma]: India nor Pakistan, but just to get their independence back. And since our whole freedom

00:00:55.400 --> 00:01:00.240
[Amit Varma]: struggle was a battle for independence from the British, who could grudge them this? Some

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:05.080
[Amit Varma]: of them, even though they were deep within present-day India, wanted to be part of Pakistan.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:08.680
[Amit Varma]: Using force on these princely states would not have gone down well with the international

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:15.080
[Amit Varma]: community, so they had to be persuaded to join India of their own free will. Our founders

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:21.480
[Amit Varma]: had a few weeks before independence to accomplish this task, which seemed almost impossible.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:25.160
[Amit Varma]: Hundreds of princely states, how do you get them all to sign on the dotted line? How do

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:29.720
[Amit Varma]: you even find the time to speak to all of them? How do you accommodate the separate

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:35.320
[Amit Varma]: demands, especially when Pakistan is also playing mischief in the background? A balkanization

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:41.500
[Amit Varma]: of India seemed inevitable, but it did not happen. Step by step, the country we now know

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:47.560
[Amit Varma]: as India was politically constructed by a handful of men. One of them, of course, is

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:53.240
[Amit Varma]: Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel, but his right-hand man, B.P. Medan, is today a footnote in most

00:01:53.240 --> 00:02:00.800
[Amit Varma]: history books, despite being arguably as important as Patel in bringing us all together. If B.P.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:08.120
[Amit Varma]: Medan did not exist, we may have been living in a different India.

