00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:15.600
[Amit Varma]: Rani, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:17.360
[Guest]: Thank you. Thank you for having me.

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:21.400
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we get to this fascinating book, that's clearly been a labor of love

00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:26.120
[Amit Varma]: for you. Tell me a little bit about yourself. You know, what are you? What's your training?

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:27.560
[Guest]: What's your education like?

00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:32.640
[Guest]: So I have basically majored in history. I went to Stevens, I majored in history, I then

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:37.280
[Guest]: switched to international relations. I didn't really know what I wanted to do post history.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:41.560
[Guest]: I knew I didn't want to get into conventional academics. I didn't want to do a PhD. I didn't

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:47.520
[Guest]: want to teach. I also didn't want to sit for the civil services. But I really enjoyed studying

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:52.560
[Guest]: about international relations, about how countries interacted with each other, diplomats interacted

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:57.680
[Guest]: with each other. So I switched to international relations. I majored in Chinese foreign policy.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:04.200
[Guest]: I specialized in US-China relations. I completed my academics up to my MPhil, and thereafter

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:09.800
[Guest]: I just I dropped out of academia 100%. I didn't want to continue to do a PhD. I took up a

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:14.600
[Guest]: job as a research analyst with the Institute of Peace and Conflict Studies, where I worked

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:19.320
[Guest]: for a couple of years as a China research analyst. It wasn't something that gave me

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:24.680
[Guest]: a lot of joy because it was not the kind of interaction with international relations that

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:28.800
[Guest]: I actually wanted to do. And at that point, I wasn't very clear about what that meant

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.440
[Guest]: either. I just knew that I wasn't very pleased with what I was doing. I also knew that I

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.760
[Guest]: wanted to write and research a lot more than the job was actually giving me the scope to

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:44.320
[Guest]: do. So I quit my job. This was about six years ago. I quit my job and I turned to writing

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:49.240
[Guest]: full time and research full time. And coincidentally, that is also the track that brought me on

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:53.520
[Guest]: to writing VP Menon because at that point I was reading. I've always been a lover of

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:58.760
[Guest]: nonfiction. I've read a lot of political and historical nonfiction biographies primarily.

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:03.160
[Guest]: And I was at that point reading a lot about modern Indian history, about how the transfer

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:09.080
[Guest]: of power came about, etc. And I would see VP Menon's name. And let me just make it clear.

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:12.120
[Guest]: I did not know at this point, VP Menon was my great grandfather.

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:14.120
[Amit Varma]: You did not know at this point?

00:06:14.120 --> 00:06:20.720
[Guest]: No, I didn't know. So this is not something that we discussed effusively at all. My mother

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:27.160
[Guest]: never and indeed members of my family didn't ever bring me up to know who VP Menon was.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:32.920
[Guest]: There was no constant eulogising of this was who your great grandfather was. But we are

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:37.640
[Guest]: a family who loves to read and we like to discuss books. So I was discussing a particular

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:43.120
[Guest]: book, I forget which, on the transfer of power. And I was mentioning VP Menon, who was perennially

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:48.360
[Guest]: referred to as in Mountbatten's able reforms commissioner, etc. And at that point I was

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:52.480
[Guest]: in my mid 20s. And my mother looked at me and she said, you do know that he was your

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.760
[Guest]: great grandfather. And that was the first time that I'd heard of him. And that completely,

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:02.280
[Guest]: it intrigued me a lot because I wanted to immediately know more about this person. And

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:08.520
[Guest]: I began to try and look him up. And I found nothing apart from his very seminal books,

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:12.720
[Guest]: the transfer of power and the story of the integration of the states. But those are written

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:18.640
[Guest]: in very academic, very concise prose. They reveal nothing. They give nothing away about

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:24.200
[Guest]: what kind of man this person was. And there was nothing else. There was no biography.

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:28.640
[Guest]: There was no autobiography. There was nothing. And I began to become more and more interested

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:34.520
[Guest]: in this person and trying to find out what kind of person this was. And that I have to

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:39.600
[Guest]: say it happened simultaneously with me losing interest in a typical desk job. So when I

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:44.760
[Guest]: dropped out, when I quit my job, this seemed like the natural thing to do, to research

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:50.600
[Guest]: who VP Menon was and what I wanted to do as far as writing his life was concerned. Did

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:55.160
[Guest]: I want to write a complete biography? Did I want to explore it into more of a political

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:59.200
[Guest]: biography? What did I want to do? It was the first time that I'd actually started playing

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:04.160
[Guest]: around with ideas like that. And that gave me a lot of joy. It gave me great freedom

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:09.200
[Guest]: to think. It gave me a lot of scope to sort of expand my horizons more. And actually how

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:11.960
[Guest]: I began writing this book and how I came to this point.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:16.880
[Amit Varma]: And so, you know, you get drawn into the stories of he's because obviously a lot of the popular

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:21.440
[Amit Varma]: books that we read about our history will mention him. He is Mountbatten's reforms commissioner.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:25.500
[Amit Varma]: He is, you know, Patel's right hand man in the state's department. But when you actually

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:28.880
[Amit Varma]: decide that you want to write a history of the guy, and you also decide that it's going

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:33.920
[Amit Varma]: to be a sort of a comprehensive history, not just his political career, it's going to include

00:08:33.920 --> 00:08:39.800
[Amit Varma]: little things like how he ran away from home and went to school when he was 13 years old.

00:08:39.800 --> 00:08:44.360
[Amit Varma]: What are the kind of sources that you then look at? Because you have the unique position

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:49.160
[Amit Varma]: of not just having access to the family, but his family is your family. So you've got a

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:54.720
[Amit Varma]: unique kind of access there. But apart from that, how do you then go about looking for

00:08:54.720 --> 00:08:59.400
[Amit Varma]: sources? What kind of access do you need for that? Were there good primary sources left?

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:05.320
[Guest]: So in terms of his professional life, there was plenty of access. And this happened in

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:11.000
[Guest]: a sort of layered way because he's left behind a collection of his professional papers, rather,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.520
[Guest]: which are housed at Teen Moorthy. Now, these have nothing to do with his personal life.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:19.440
[Guest]: They are just basically his career in government service. And that is the V.P. Menon collection.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:22.940
[Guest]: Apart from that, I also had to go through the professional papers of nearly everyone

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:28.120
[Guest]: who was involved in the transfer of power. So Batten, Nehru, Krishna Menon, the Sardar

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:33.200
[Guest]: Patel correspondence, because in every one of these people's correspondence, in between

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:38.240
[Guest]: the pages, there were different memos, there were letters written by V.P. to these guys,

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:42.800
[Guest]: and these guys were corresponding with him in turn, which have merited footnotes in transfer

00:09:42.800 --> 00:09:47.420
[Guest]: of power narratives, but never really been looked at. So these, to me, were also a huge

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:51.800
[Guest]: insight into how this man was thinking. So that was one source.

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:56.320
[Guest]: As far as his personal life was concerned, I hit several roadblocks because he was a

00:09:56.320 --> 00:10:02.280
[Guest]: very, very fiercely private man. He was not somebody who was an eloquent diarist or an

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:08.240
[Guest]: eloquent letter writer. He left behind very few instances of how he felt at a particular

00:10:08.240 --> 00:10:14.160
[Guest]: point, of how he experienced his own personal, for instance, his arrival in Delhi and stuff

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:19.640
[Guest]: like that. There are letters that have been left few and far between. There are letters

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:24.160
[Guest]: that were left to his stepdaughter, Meenakshi Anantan. One or two letters have survived

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:28.000
[Guest]: that were left to his brother, to whom he was extremely close. And he was the eldest

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.600
[Guest]: of seven siblings. So he was very close to one particular younger brother with whom he

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:32.600
[Amit Varma]: used to correspond.

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:36.440
[Amit Varma]: I thought he was the oldest boy. He had an elder sister who got married? Or am I confused?

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:41.880
[Guest]: He had, his elder sister is not really talked about because she died long before he was.

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:42.880
[Amit Varma]: So effectively, he was the oldest.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:48.220
[Guest]: So effectively, he was the eldest of the family. And these were letters that didn't allow me

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:54.200
[Guest]: much insight into the man as such because he very rarely talked about, for instance,

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:58.440
[Guest]: his transition from boyhood to manhood. You know, when he talked about his arrival in

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:04.360
[Guest]: Delhi, it was only at a specific point in time. So he wasn't very vocal about things

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:09.560
[Guest]: like that, about his emotions, about his feelings. So it was a labor, I have to say, a long,

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:14.680
[Guest]: long labor because in the process of this, I've had to connect to members of the Vapala

00:11:14.680 --> 00:11:21.240
[Guest]: clan whom I didn't know at all. Because when VP left Kerala and when he ran away to Kolar

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:25.240
[Guest]: and moved to Delhi and Simla, he used to return to Kerala, but he never really returned to

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:28.120
[Guest]: settle in Kerala. He retired in Bangalore.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:33.440
[Guest]: So his children grew up out of the main Tarawad, which by the way, still exists, but nobody

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:39.480
[Guest]: ever really returned, at least not from my family. So there was no touch that was maintained

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:44.680
[Guest]: between members of his children's families, for instance, his siblings' families. There

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:48.720
[Guest]: was no contact that was maintained. And this was in the days before emails and telephones

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:54.640
[Guest]: and mobiles and stuff like that. So to try and hunt them down was extremely difficult.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:59.120
[Guest]: It was a matter of chance that I actually discovered somebody via Twitter, actually,

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:04.880
[Guest]: who actually led me to look at Kochi and Arunakulam, where I discovered his brother's children

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:10.960
[Guest]: are still living there. So it brought me home in many ways. It's brought me back to my roots

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:16.520
[Guest]: in ways that I didn't think was possible. The entire clan actually pulled together and

00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:22.160
[Guest]: retrieved old letters or scraps of information, photographs, which are now in the book, which

00:12:22.160 --> 00:12:27.400
[Guest]: have existed and allowed me to piece together really painstakingly the story of this man

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:33.760
[Guest]: from nothing, you know, because he was so completely, almost as if he lived in a little

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:39.360
[Guest]: bubble in which there was his immediate family, and there was his job. And very rarely did

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:45.400
[Guest]: he go beyond that. He loved his brother, he adored his mother, but he was not somebody

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:52.140
[Guest]: who was very vocal about his emotional life, nor was he someone who was particularly sentimental.

00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:57.920
[Guest]: So he didn't leave behind any trace of a softer side of VP. In fact, the only soft side that

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:04.600
[Guest]: I could find was his great love for his second wife, and his immense love for his stepdaughter,

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:10.600
[Guest]: Meenakshi. And surprisingly, he has been very vocal there. So that was the only soft side

00:13:10.600 --> 00:13:17.560
[Guest]: of VP that I could find. And it's been a search that's intrigued me a lot, because I don't

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:23.520
[Guest]: think it's this hard to piece together someone's life. And yet, it's been incredibly difficult.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:29.520
[Guest]: His first marriage, for instance, there is little to no information that survives about

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:34.360
[Guest]: who he married. We just have a first name, Susheela. We don't even have a last name.

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:39.840
[Guest]: We don't know what family she came from. We know vaguely that she was from the same village.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:44.440
[Guest]: We don't know what she looked like. There are no photographs, there are no letters.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:49.160
[Guest]: There is nothing that survives. We don't know why that marriage broke down. We know that

00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:54.280
[Guest]: it wasn't a particularly happy marriage, and that's about all we know. We know that there

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:59.240
[Guest]: were two sons from that marriage. I am descended from her eldest son. And beyond that, we know

00:13:59.240 --> 00:14:04.680
[Guest]: nothing else. Why this marriage broke down in 1935, why it broke down, we don't know.

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:09.480
[Guest]: We know that there was no attempt to contact her sons after she left. If there was, either

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:14.320
[Guest]: those letters were intercepted and then destroyed, because nothing survives today. That to me

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:22.040
[Guest]: spoke of a rather ruthless side of VP. It was not a side that I personally identify

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:27.080
[Guest]: with. Certainly, it was a side that his children never understood. It was also an aspect that

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:33.640
[Guest]: impacted his children for years, if not all of their lives, because my grandfather was

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:38.360
[Guest]: about nine when the marriage broke apart. His brother was seven, and they were young.

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:42.520
[Guest]: But I mean, to have this happen, and at that scale, when you're that young, or indeed when

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:49.600
[Guest]: you're any age, is life changing for you. And, you know, he never, never remembered

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:53.880
[Guest]: his mother. And that's another aspect that I found bizarre, because obviously, the hurt

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:59.720
[Guest]: of his mother's exit impacted him so deeply that he never had any memory of what she was

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:01.840
[Amit Varma]: like. So there are no memories of...

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:06.680
[Amit Varma]: This was at the context, she basically disappeared one day, and she never got in touch again.

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:10.160
[Amit Varma]: And you have a moving story in your book about how some 30 years later...

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:15.200
[Guest]: Yes. My mother remembered that story. It was something she never forgot. They were in a

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:21.440
[Guest]: busy marketplace. And suddenly he said, there's my mother right there. And he ran out of the

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:26.560
[Guest]: shop, and it was a busy street outside. And the woman who had stored some instinct in

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:32.160
[Guest]: him had disappeared. But to me, that was incredibly poignant, because it spoke of a little boy

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:37.720
[Guest]: who never stopped looking for his mother. And it also speaks to me of the kind of hurt

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:42.600
[Guest]: a parent is capable of inflicting on their children. And I have tried to put down the

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:48.600
[Guest]: story in complete full as much as I know it, because I don't believe that even if you do

00:15:48.600 --> 00:15:53.360
[Guest]: have a cruel streak, if you have a particularly ruthless streak, that that should be set aside.

00:15:53.360 --> 00:15:58.120
[Guest]: Because to me, it spoke a lot about the fact that this was a man who went on to do wonderful

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:04.120
[Guest]: things for this country, but was capable of immense cruelty in his personal life. He was

00:16:04.120 --> 00:16:08.720
[Guest]: not a very good father to his sons. He was very emotionally distant. They grew up craving

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:14.320
[Guest]: his love, his approval. They always wanted his validation. And strangely, they called

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:21.760
[Guest]: him sir, which again spoke of a very stern, formal aspect of the paternal relationship.

00:16:21.760 --> 00:16:27.920
[Guest]: On the other hand, he adored his stepdaughter. She was with him when he died. He wanted everything

00:16:27.920 --> 00:16:34.240
[Guest]: after he was dead to be left to her. And she adored him in turn. So he was obviously a

00:16:34.240 --> 00:16:40.240
[Guest]: very complex man. So to try and deconstruct that from next to nothing has been hard, very,

00:16:40.240 --> 00:16:41.240
[Guest]: very hard.

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:44.800
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say, you know, when I was reading the book, I thought, okay, there are two sort

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:49.480
[Amit Varma]: of challenges in front of you. And one which you've just elaborated upon is when so little

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:52.960
[Amit Varma]: is known of his personal life, and there's nothing left. And he was not really a person

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:57.120
[Amit Varma]: who wrote personal letters or stayed in touch with his family. How do you piece a personal

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:00.840
[Amit Varma]: life together? That's one challenge. But the other challenge is actually with his political

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:08.680
[Amit Varma]: and public life, which is a challenge of figuring out with your additional material, what sense

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:13.600
[Amit Varma]: to make of the conflicting narratives. Because in a lot of the key moments in history, like

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:18.200
[Amit Varma]: for example, his relationship with Mountbatten, Mountbatten was a self aggrandizing man who

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:21.640
[Amit Varma]: took credit for everything. In fact, what is now called the Mountbatten plan, as you

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:26.360
[Unknown]: pointed out, was drafted by men in years before Mountbatten even came to India. It's called

00:17:26.360 --> 00:17:30.800
[Amit Varma]: the Men in Plan. And you know, so Mountbatten made it a point to try and take credit for

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:35.120
[Amit Varma]: everything that was happening in a similar sense. Patel was given a lot of the credit

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:41.080
[Amit Varma]: for the behind the scenes work that VP did. There are all kinds of conflicting accounts

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:45.640
[Amit Varma]: of what's really going on there, because there are the egos of all these big players on the

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:50.460
[Amit Varma]: stage, and they're all putting forward their side of the story. Was that a sort of challenge

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:54.720
[Amit Varma]: for you that how do you build a coherent narrative out of this? Because VP is obviously also

00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:59.800
[Amit Varma]: got his strong points of view when it comes to all of this. And at times they don't match

00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:02.160
[Guest]: up with the others. So how do you make sense of that?

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:07.960
[Guest]: That was something that I found, I initially thought of this as a challenge, right? Because

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:13.000
[Guest]: essentially, though he never sat for his ICS examinations, this guy was a bureaucrat. How

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:20.160
[Guest]: do you make a bureaucrat stand out political giants? You know, he is walking among legends.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:26.320
[Guest]: He is at a point which is a crossroads in India's modern history. How do you make somebody,

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: and it's so easy to stereotype a bureaucrat, right? You think of them as a babu pushing

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:35.240
[Guest]: paper. And it was a fascinating aspect for me, because when you're talking, when you're

00:18:35.240 --> 00:18:41.360
[Guest]: talking on independence movement, you don't necessarily like to think of it as paperwork,

00:18:41.360 --> 00:18:47.320
[Guest]: personnel shortages, transfers of personnel. You don't like to think of it like that because

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:51.800
[Guest]: it's generally, it's a boring aspect. You know, revolution generally makes you think

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:57.320
[Guest]: of bloodshed and stirring speeches and wonderful leaders. You don't think of the civil servants

00:18:57.320 --> 00:19:02.560
[Guest]: who are actually doing the work behind the scenes. So my greatest fear was how do I pull

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:07.400
[Guest]: out VP Menon from the shadows of the kind of history he was involved with, from the

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:13.880
[Guest]: kind of people he was involved with and make him stand out on his own. To that end, I found

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:21.160
[Guest]: that the 18 hours of interviews that Hodgson did with him in 1965, they were a goldmine.

00:19:21.160 --> 00:19:27.600
[Guest]: They've never been looked at in any narrative of the transfer of power. And to me, this

00:19:27.600 --> 00:19:33.400
[Guest]: was, it was almost criminal because you had his voice. It was him narrating how he had

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:40.920
[Guest]: actually worked through from 1918 onwards to 1951. And it brought his story into really

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:45.360
[Guest]: vivid life for me, which is why I've allowed his voice to do most of the talking in the

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:50.680
[Guest]: biography because for me, there was no other person who could tell it better. It was also

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:56.860
[Guest]: a challenge to me to try and understand how he might have felt given the fact that he

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:00.760
[Guest]: had just started out in government service when the independence movement was gaining

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:07.000
[Guest]: steam and what he must have felt as somebody who's sitting within the walls of the Imperial

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:12.480
[Guest]: Secretariat while his countrymen are clamoring to be free of colonial rule. Was there a moral

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:20.280
[Guest]: dilemma? Did he ever feel any kind of conflict? And in those tapes, there is my answer because

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:28.000
[Guest]: it turns out he did feel that kind of conflict. He genuinely was somebody who believed that,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:34.360
[Guest]: look, I feel like I can work better against the system if I'm within the system. If I

00:20:34.360 --> 00:20:40.520
[Guest]: can do, if I can bring about any kind of constitutional progress, that can be my contribution to this

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:45.600
[Guest]: country's fight for independence. I don't necessarily have to be out there in public

00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:50.720
[Guest]: meetings in a protest, which other people are doing already. This is one way in which

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:56.520
[Guest]: I can contribute. And it also sidetracked me into wondering whether this was just VP

00:20:56.520 --> 00:20:59.800
[Guest]: who thought like this or were there other people who thought like this? And it turns

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:04.800
[Guest]: out that there were. H. V. R. Iyengar, for instance, in his oral histories, which he's

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:10.120
[Guest]: left behind at Teen Moorthy, tells this lovely story of how, you know, a lot of people in

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:14.720
[Guest]: the civil service, including Iyengar, was so conflicted about how to deal with this

00:21:14.720 --> 00:21:19.000
[Guest]: conundrum that they went to Sardar Patel and they said, look, are we doing something wrong

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.560
[Guest]: here? Shouldn't we be also rebelling like our countrymen are? And the Sardar thought

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:27.800
[Guest]: about this for a minute and then he said, no, you know, I mean, when India finally does

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:31.560
[Guest]: become independent, we're going to need people who are trained. We're going to need people

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:37.000
[Guest]: who've been there, done that and have experience in administration, in the do's and don'ts

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.400
[Guest]: of governance. So there should be no conundrum. You're doing what is right and will eventually

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:46.200
[Guest]: be right for this country because you will be inducted into an independent India civil

00:21:46.200 --> 00:21:50.680
[Guest]: service. So actually speaking, it wasn't just VP who felt this way. It was there were other

00:21:50.680 --> 00:21:55.800
[Guest]: people who felt that way as well. In the course, nearly four decades in government, VP was

00:21:55.800 --> 00:22:02.560
[Guest]: exposed to egos that were huge, personalities that were huge. Often they were too huge to

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:08.680
[Guest]: be contained around the same table. And for him, as he's telling the story, it is essentially

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:14.740
[Guest]: a sort of clash of different personalities and egos at play that is actually going towards

00:22:14.740 --> 00:22:20.560
[Guest]: making history what it is. You know, you had immensely petty arguments. You had immensely

00:22:20.560 --> 00:22:25.480
[Guest]: vicious arguments also sometimes because these were high pressure situations, particularly

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:31.520
[Guest]: as the country moved into the 1940s. Tempers were high, you know, egos were huge. Vanity

00:22:31.520 --> 00:22:37.080
[Guest]: was perennially getting wounded. And this man had to navigate so many different kinds

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:41.360
[Guest]: of personalities. And this was not just during the transfer of power, but in post transfer

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:45.680
[Guest]: of power during integration as well. For me, this was a fascinating sort of tapestry because

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:50.680
[Guest]: you had VP actually talking his way around different personalities. For instance, with

00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:54.840
[Guest]: Mountbatten, he had to present his own plan to make it seem like it was Mountbatten's

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:59.240
[Guest]: idea because he knew that Mountbatten liked to take the credit and like to be center stage.

00:22:59.240 --> 00:23:04.520
[Guest]: So he developed a knack for sort of adapting his ideas to those who are in power so that

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:09.420
[Guest]: it would seem like their idea, which is, I think, a major reason why his own contribution

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:16.300
[Guest]: has been so downplayed, why it's easy to efface VP Menon from the face of modern Indian history.

00:23:16.300 --> 00:23:21.640
[Guest]: Because of this particular knack, because he found it best often to let others take

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:28.800
[Guest]: credit for ideas that potentially were game changers. And that to me was another challenge

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:34.120
[Guest]: while I was writing this book, because while in his official narratives, he's allowed people

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:40.120
[Guest]: to take the credit, in his oral history, he's very clear about certain things. And in other

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:46.080
[Guest]: people's oral histories as well, Alan Campbell Johnson, Mountbatten himself, H.V.R. Iyengar,

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:51.600
[Guest]: everyone is equally clear that VP Menon did most of the work. There was no one in power

00:23:51.600 --> 00:23:58.240
[Guest]: at that point who did not command as much influence as VP. In fact, even when the Partition

00:23:58.240 --> 00:24:03.400
[Guest]: Council was set up, Iyengar remembers that every decision was run by, he would sign off

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:08.240
[Guest]: on it even though he wasn't necessarily involved in every single committee that was operating

00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:14.080
[Guest]: under the council. For me, that's been a fascinating eye-opener and a great insight into how the

00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:20.040
[Guest]: wheels of power were actually turning at that point. There was a lot happening. It was not

00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:24.120
[Guest]: necessarily as black and white as we see it today because everything was happening so

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:30.720
[Guest]: fast and there were events of momentous scale happening almost simultaneously. So to actually

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:37.800
[Guest]: be in boats at once and navigate such different personalities at the same time required some

00:24:37.800 --> 00:24:38.800
[Amit Varma]: doing.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:44.440
[Amit Varma]: And he was a doer. Let's kind of get back to biography. And you know, his childhood

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:51.160
[Amit Varma]: was infinitely fascinating to me because you know, he's growing up in the village and he's

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:56.480
[Amit Varma]: a headmaster's son and he's, you know, sent to school and all of that. And at some point

00:24:56.480 --> 00:25:01.520
[Amit Varma]: this Tamilian headmaster at a future school basically kicks him out. And then you quote

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:06.120
[Amit Varma]: his own words, like he's very upset. He goes to the banks of the river, presumably cries

00:25:06.120 --> 00:25:11.440
[Amit Varma]: a bit, kicks the trees. And then he says, quote, I found an empty liquor bottle on the

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:16.320
[Amit Varma]: banks of the river. It gave me an idea. I didn't bother to think about it or even about

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:21.520
[Amit Varma]: the consequences. I just wanted that Tamilian to pay for what he had done. I went to the

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:27.160
[Amit Varma]: shop and I told Ahmed, who was the shopkeeper, and I told Ahmed, I wanted some kerosene oil

00:25:27.160 --> 00:25:32.680
[Amit Varma]: in a matchbox. My mother would send the money later, stop quote. And then he goes and burns

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:33.680
[Guest]: down his school.

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:39.280
[Guest]: Actually, this was a completely sensational reading. I mean, today, the few people who

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:43.520
[Guest]: actually remember V.P. Menon remember the story of a boy who burned down the school.

00:25:43.520 --> 00:25:47.400
[Guest]: This was the Autopalem High School, which was basically the common point for most children

00:25:47.400 --> 00:25:52.280
[Guest]: to come and study. He actually did set it on fire when I actually asked around. Descendants

00:25:52.280 --> 00:25:56.120
[Guest]: of people who had actually gone to Autopalem High School attested to the fact that V.P.

00:25:56.120 --> 00:26:01.000
[Guest]: had actually set the school on fire. It didn't completely burn down. It burned down halfway.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:02.960
[Guest]: But yeah, he did set it on fire.

00:26:02.960 --> 00:26:03.960
[Guest]: And he's 13 years old.

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:08.640
[Guest]: And he's 13 years old. I mean, there are lots of us who have been 13 and have wanted to

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:12.760
[Guest]: burn our schools down too. This boy actually did it. And what was even more interesting

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:17.120
[Guest]: to me was that he was so overcome with shame because he'd just been carried away by this

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:22.200
[Guest]: rage. And he was then so overcome with horror at what he'd done that he actually ran away

00:26:22.200 --> 00:26:23.200
[Amit Varma]: from home.

00:26:23.200 --> 00:26:24.200
[Amit Varma]: The same night.

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:29.440
[Guest]: The same night. And he actually hitches a ride on a train and it carries him to Kolar.

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:35.320
[Guest]: And he begins a life there, which is completely alien to the life that he's lived in before.

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:42.000
[Guest]: He's been this really pampered little boy. His mother adored him. He adored his mother.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.360
[Guest]: He never really did a hard day's work in his life. And here he is suddenly lobbing up in

00:26:46.360 --> 00:26:52.120
[Guest]: a gold mine to take up the life of a coolie boy. And he never done any such kind of work

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:57.320
[Guest]: in his life before. So, I mean, he suddenly basically changed his life overnight by this

00:26:57.320 --> 00:27:02.840
[Guest]: one hot-headed act. And his life would never be the same again. He would not go back home

00:27:02.840 --> 00:27:07.720
[Guest]: until it was time for him to get married. He wanted to actually make something of himself

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:12.920
[Guest]: because by this point he's thinking, I've basically set my school on fire. I brought

00:27:12.920 --> 00:27:18.040
[Guest]: shame to my family. What will my mother think of me? I have to now make something of myself

00:27:18.040 --> 00:27:20.240
[Guest]: to make up for whatever I've done.

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:25.160
[Guest]: And he goes to Kolar and he spends five years of his life, five of the most formative years

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:30.200
[Guest]: of any child's life, working in a gold mine, first as a coolie. And then he applies with

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:36.280
[Guest]: what I thought was great brazenness for the job of an overseer. And to me, that spoke

00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:43.200
[Guest]: right there of somebody who had almost blind ambition and actually really didn't care what

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:48.080
[Guest]: anyone might think. Because, I mean, this is a boy who's not completed his formal schooling,

00:27:48.080 --> 00:27:54.960
[Guest]: right? He's not got an examination certificate, but he has the audacity to go to a supervisor

00:27:54.960 --> 00:27:59.360
[Guest]: and basically say, look, I want to apply for this post. And the supervisor gives him the

00:27:59.360 --> 00:28:03.680
[Guest]: post. And it's something that actually marks his career, that will mark his career and

00:28:03.680 --> 00:28:08.360
[Guest]: his personality as the years go by, because he's then now prone to doing this. He will

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:13.920
[Guest]: do it again in 1914 when he applies to the registrar of the Home Department and basically

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:18.160
[Guest]: says, look, give me a job in the Directorate of Statistics, you know, which is a new department

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:23.640
[Guest]: that's been set up by the Raj to essentially collect really boring statistical information

00:28:23.640 --> 00:28:30.400
[Guest]: about things like crop output and demographics and rainfall. And he has worked his way northwards

00:28:30.400 --> 00:28:32.680
[Guest]: from Kolar by this point. It is five years later.

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:38.080
[Amit Varma]: We are getting ahead of ourselves. Can I interrupt you and kind of go back? What I found, you

00:28:38.080 --> 00:28:43.960
[Amit Varma]: know, you should say sorry for getting in the way of your narrative. No, what I found

00:28:43.960 --> 00:28:48.600
[Amit Varma]: interesting even, you know, back at Ottapalam, there's a couple of things. One, you point

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:52.960
[Amit Varma]: out very evocatively the time that he would be waiting for his train at Ottapalam railway

00:28:52.960 --> 00:28:57.880
[Amit Varma]: station. And all the people would look after him. He's 12 and 13 now and all of that. And

00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:01.320
[Amit Varma]: they're giving him little things to eat and drink. And then one day, one of them gives

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:06.240
[Amit Varma]: him the Madras Mail, the newspaper. And from that day, every single day, he's reading every

00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:11.760
[Amit Varma]: single page. He's just sitting there and he's devouring. And he's a kid. He's 12 years old.

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:15.720
[Amit Varma]: He's 13 years old at the time he burns the school down. And this kind of struck me, this

00:29:15.720 --> 00:29:20.520
[Amit Varma]: hunger to know everything about the world. Of course, if one of them gave him a smartphone

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:24.520
[Amit Varma]: with PUBG on it, we don't know what would have happened. But no, he's got this hunger

00:29:24.520 --> 00:29:29.520
[Amit Varma]: for knowledge. The other thing that struck me is on how you point out, and then you quote

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:34.880
[Amit Varma]: him on this, that as the train, he gets on the train when he's running away from home.

00:29:34.880 --> 00:29:40.440
[Amit Varma]: And then you quote him saying, quote, that train and forgive my pronunciations, my Mallu

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:45.560
[Amit Varma]: friends. I am in spirit one of you, but my pronunciations are not so great. This is VP

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:50.760
[Amit Varma]: Menon saying, quote, that train went from Ottapallam to Lakhiri and then Parli and then

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:55.800
[Amit Varma]: on to Olavakode. We went through a tunnel at Valayar and then we stopped at Pothanur.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:30:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is, he's remembering this in the 1960s. This is part of his oral, the history

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:05.840
[Amit Varma]: that he recorded then. So, you know, almost 50 years later, more than 50 years later,

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:07.880
[Guest]: he remembers all the stops.

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:13.680
[Guest]: What I find that Nohans actually pointed this out is that he had an eidetic memory and that

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.680
[Guest]: is something that would serve him immensely.

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:17.520
[Amit Varma]: That's like a photographic memory.

00:30:17.520 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: Yeah, photographic memory. So basically he never forgot anything. And it's something

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:28.360
[Guest]: that came in incredibly importantly in his career. It would come in recollecting memory.

00:30:28.360 --> 00:30:33.400
[Guest]: And as you said, he was always characterized by this really strong hunger to learn. It

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:37.800
[Guest]: makes you actually wistful thinking of a small boy on a railway platform in the middle of

00:30:37.800 --> 00:30:43.240
[Guest]: nowhere, actually going through paper after paper, reading about events that he really

00:30:43.240 --> 00:30:48.240
[Guest]: has no idea what is going on, you know, and he's reading about things like the partition

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:53.560
[Guest]: in Bengal and he's reading about, you know, political debates about international events.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:58.800
[Guest]: And he has no clue who these people are or why it's happening at all, because life in

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:02.680
[Guest]: rural Kerala is worlds away from whatever might be happening.

00:31:02.680 --> 00:31:06.560
[Guest]: But it doesn't stop him from thinking about these things, from having questions in his

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:11.320
[Guest]: head that obviously no one can answer for him at that point. But to me, sitting a little

00:31:11.320 --> 00:31:17.240
[Guest]: boy sitting on a platform with, you know, a cup of chai or coffee and vada and idli

00:31:17.240 --> 00:31:22.680
[Guest]: and reading the papers and reading about these men who signed pieces of papers to change

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:28.320
[Guest]: history and reconnecting the dots years later when he's actually one of those men signing

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:33.960
[Guest]: papers and making history. It was as if life had come full circle. But he was always characterized

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:41.160
[Guest]: by a strong desire to learn. It was something that he utilized as he grew up. And I saw

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:47.920
[Guest]: it more and more as he entered government service. He had this knack for taking wadges

00:31:47.920 --> 00:31:53.440
[Guest]: of knowledge and adapting it to a particular situation, depending on what position in government

00:31:53.440 --> 00:31:58.280
[Guest]: service he was, and also depending on the kind of person he was dealing with. So that

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:03.000
[Guest]: is something that he developed very early on because he had such a head for figures,

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:09.200
[Guest]: facts, for remembering entire pages of information. I remember my mother once telling me that

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:14.400
[Guest]: he could read one paragraph in the heaviest constitutional prose and you could ask him

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:19.400
[Guest]: that same paragraph a week later and he would recite it word for word. And it's something

00:32:19.400 --> 00:32:25.280
[Guest]: that I really enjoyed because it's a characteristic that sounds cliched when you actually talk

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:30.640
[Guest]: about it, but it was something that was so reflected in how he actually worked his way

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:36.960
[Guest]: up and how he utilized that knowledge that I found myself believing it. This was somebody

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:42.720
[Guest]: who liked to learn. This was somebody for whom information was, it was pleasure. He

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:48.960
[Guest]: liked learning and he liked figures, facts. He wanted to know what made the heart of something

00:32:48.960 --> 00:32:53.520
[Guest]: tick. He wanted to read around it. He wanted to read about it. It was something that never

00:32:53.520 --> 00:32:58.520
[Guest]: left him right until the day he died. So yeah, that was very fascinating for me.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And yet he wasn't a bookish kid. He was a man of action or at that point, a kid of action

00:33:02.840 --> 00:33:07.040
[Unknown]: like you point out, he burns his school, which is not, by the way, something we recommend

00:33:07.040 --> 00:33:11.920
[Amit Varma]: to 13 year old listeners of this show. You know, there are, I mean, yeah, that survivorship

00:33:11.920 --> 00:33:16.680
[Amit Varma]: bias, he got away with it, but you know, you won't, don't try it at home. And what I'm

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:20.720
[Amit Varma]: also struck by is the same night he decides to leave, but he doesn't just leave. He figures

00:33:20.720 --> 00:33:25.000
[Amit Varma]: out where he's going to go. In his own words, I had heard of the gold fields in Kolar. I

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:29.600
[Amit Varma]: knew I needed money to eat. That was the only thought in my head, how to fill my stomach.

00:33:29.600 --> 00:33:35.480
[Amit Varma]: So there's this pampered entitled kid who runs away. And now you've given some perspective

00:33:35.480 --> 00:33:40.320
[Amit Varma]: on what Kolar is in your book, which I think for the listeners is actually pretty useful.

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:44.360
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote that bit again. How does it feel listening to your words in my voice?

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:52.280
[Amit Varma]: Very strange. Anyway, I'll read this bit out again, because I think it's important perspective

00:33:52.280 --> 00:33:56.920
[Amit Varma]: when you just to imagine a 13 year old kid in this place, quote, the legend of Kolar's

00:33:56.920 --> 00:34:02.200
[Amit Varma]: might was not to be trifled with. In 1897, a deadly rockfall and landslide inside the

00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:08.360
[Amit Varma]: Mysore mine had killed upwards of 50 workers, injuring hundreds more. In January 1906, the

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:14.000
[Amit Varma]: wicker roof of one of the mining cages caught fire killing six workers and injuring 10 others.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:19.120
[Amit Varma]: Sickness was a constant specter. Cholera, dysentery, malaria, asthma, and lung cancer

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:23.320
[Amit Varma]: raged through the coolie settlements, picking off those who survived the horrors of the

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:28.040
[Amit Varma]: underground. When dusk fell, workers would stumble out of their minds and their workstations

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:33.080
[Amit Varma]: and many would turn their faces towards the local liquor shops or gambling dens. Even

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:37.600
[Amit Varma]: the wives and children waited for them at home. The sky was perennially contaminated

00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:42.680
[Amit Varma]: by smoke billowing from the tall brick chimneys that dotted the fields. The horizon was marred

00:34:42.680 --> 00:34:47.080
[Amit Varma]: by a huge contraption with rotating wheels on top. He would later learn that this was

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:51.640
[Amit Varma]: a great lift that conveyed men from the surface of the earth to his bowels. The mines rumbled

00:34:51.640 --> 00:34:56.560
[Amit Varma]: all day long with the occasional explosion, dynamite blasting through rock, shaking the

00:34:56.560 --> 00:35:03.120
[Amit Varma]: earth and showering the debris and dust on workers in the adjacent narrow passes. Temperatures

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:09.480
[Amit Varma]: raged up to 157 degrees Fahrenheit. And the temperature is of course inside the mines.

00:35:09.480 --> 00:35:14.640
[Amit Varma]: And what also struck me, what you pointed out is that the Englishmen that he dealt with

00:35:14.640 --> 00:35:18.640
[Amit Varma]: at this point in time did not care that he did not have a school leaving certificate

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:23.920
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. They were willing to evaluate him on his own merits. And this is exactly

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:28.240
[Amit Varma]: a trope that continues for the rest of his life, where he rises to the top of the civil

00:35:28.240 --> 00:35:34.280
[Amit Varma]: service without giving the ICS examination. And at every step, it is, you know, even when

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:40.280
[Amit Varma]: he's sort of treated badly, like when Mountbatten first comes to India, he's a reforms commissioner,

00:35:40.280 --> 00:35:43.280
[Amit Varma]: but Mountbatten's got his own team and he wants nothing to do with him. But then at

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:48.040
[Amit Varma]: some point, he doesn't have a choice because VP is simply the best brain out there. And

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:53.440
[Amit Varma]: he kind of has to work with it. So, you know, so kind of Kolar happens and you point out

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:58.880
[Amit Varma]: about how Kolar taught him to be thrifty because he was earning so little and he wanted to

00:35:58.880 --> 00:36:03.400
[Amit Varma]: send money home. And how it taught him to compartmentalize his emotions into separate

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:09.320
[Amit Varma]: watertight boxes, which you say will be, became a blessing and a curse in later years. So

00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:12.640
[Amit Varma]: when you say it became a blessing and a curse in later years, I'm presuming you mean it

00:36:12.640 --> 00:36:17.200
[Guest]: became a blessing in the workspace. Yes, it was not a curse at home. Absolutely. It was

00:36:17.200 --> 00:36:23.320
[Amit Varma]: anything but a blessing at home. So from here, from Kolar, he then, this young teenager then

00:36:23.320 --> 00:36:29.200
[Guest]: lands up in Bombay. Yeah. Tell me about this. For one, I agree when you say he encountered

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:33.560
[Guest]: really supportive English supervisors through the rest of his career and his life. And which

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:38.960
[Guest]: is why I found Kolar completely fascinating. Because like I said, they're transformative

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:44.280
[Guest]: years for any child's life. For VP, they've changed him completely in ways that I think

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:48.360
[Guest]: he didn't even expect. And when we're talking about a pampered, privileged kid running off

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:54.880
[Guest]: to Kolar, I think it also speaks a lot about a kid who was incredibly practical and had

00:36:54.880 --> 00:36:59.520
[Guest]: a lot of pride as well. He knew that he needed food to eat, but he also knew that he was

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:04.640
[Guest]: not going to go home, face his parents and, you know, admit to what he'd done. He'd much

00:37:04.640 --> 00:37:10.480
[Guest]: rather go off, try to do something that makes something of himself and send money back home.

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:18.240
[Guest]: It's incredibly self-sufficient. It is a survival tactic. It also speaks of a lot, like I said,

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:23.960
[Guest]: a lot of practicality and pride. He is blessed completely when he meets supervisors who don't

00:37:23.960 --> 00:37:29.000
[Guest]: want a matriculation examination certificate. It is the first time that he actually encounters

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:33.680
[Guest]: someone who says, it doesn't matter what your credentials are at a piece of paper, don't

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:38.800
[Guest]: matter. And that's something that he's going to carry with him for the rest of his life.

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:44.160
[Guest]: And we can talk about that later, of course, but, you know, when he gets sacked from Kolar,

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:50.600
[Guest]: he basically starts working his way northwards. And the information here is incredibly sketchy.

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:56.120
[Guest]: There is a point when he's first gone to Bangalore, where he works as a clerk in the Imperial

00:37:56.120 --> 00:38:01.920
[Guest]: Tobacco Company. From there, he goes to Indore and these are events that have been pieced

00:38:01.920 --> 00:38:08.640
[Guest]: together from what he told various other people. So there is a lot of oral history here, but

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:15.080
[Guest]: also recollections of what others remembered of VP's childhood as well. So he also went

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:20.640
[Guest]: to Indore to try and teach the kid of a landed gentleman English. He then ends up in Bombay

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:26.120
[Guest]: and he is selling hand towels outside Victoria Terminus. And again, not a life that he's

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:31.600
[Guest]: used to. He's done several menial things along the way by now. Selling towels doesn't seem

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:38.040
[Guest]: to be anything different. And he's essentially going through a period of great emotional

00:38:38.040 --> 00:38:43.440
[Guest]: turmoil, understandably so. He goes to sleep one day and he wakes up to find that his gold

00:38:43.440 --> 00:38:49.320
[Guest]: eardrop has been stolen. And he's almost in tears because he's now been away from home

00:38:49.320 --> 00:38:54.760
[Guest]: for so long. And he's now been on his own for so long and fending for himself for so

00:38:54.760 --> 00:38:59.800
[Guest]: long that on one hand, it's become almost part of his character. On the other hand,

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:03.560
[Guest]: he's still a boy who misses home and misses his mother. And he doesn't know what he's

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:11.480
[Guest]: doing here. And these to me are moments where the boy is becoming a man, but very reluctantly

00:39:11.480 --> 00:39:17.640
[Guest]: so. They are experiences that are teaching him extremely hard things. I don't think any...

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:20.520
[Amit Varma]: He's been cruelly pushed into manhood rather than I guess becoming a man.

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:24.760
[Guest]: Yeah, it's not a simple transition for him, you know, because and it's, let me say right

00:39:24.760 --> 00:39:28.920
[Guest]: now that this was a choice he made when he chose to run away from home. Indeed, when

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:31.960
[Guest]: he chose to set his school on fire, it was a choice that he made.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:36.760
[Amit Varma]: This was a choice made for him by whoever left that empty liquor bottle on the, you

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:41.480
[Amit Varma]: know, seashore. Had he just carried the bottle away, the idea might not have stopped V.P.

00:39:41.480 --> 00:39:42.200
[Guest]: Menon. Who knows?

00:39:43.400 --> 00:39:48.120
[Guest]: So, I mean, you know, he's essentially, the transition from boyhood to manhood has not

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:54.360
[Guest]: been simple so far. He's had to, he's been kicked out of several jobs. He has basically,

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:58.760
[Guest]: he feels like he's let down his family in more ways than one. By this point, his father's

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:03.800
[Guest]: also died. His mother is not doing so well either. And he thinks, and he's plagued by

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:09.960
[Guest]: the thought that he might just end up being a nobody from nowhere. And again, fate steps

00:40:09.960 --> 00:40:15.400
[Guest]: in and he is given, he's chanced upon by this gentleman who, English gentleman who works

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:19.400
[Guest]: in the Government of India in the Home Department. Now, who this person is, we don't know. We

00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:23.720
[Guest]: merely know that he was given a letter of recommendation, which he was instructed to

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:29.080
[Guest]: carry to Delhi. And he was basically told that, look, you go to the Government of India

00:40:29.080 --> 00:40:34.680
[Guest]: and you basically use this letter to apply for a job. And he does that because by this

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:39.080
[Guest]: point, he doesn't know what else to do. So he goes off there. At this point, he doesn't

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:43.640
[Guest]: even know that he has to sit for the ICS examinations. I think that's a thought that never crossed

00:40:43.640 --> 00:40:48.200
[Guest]: his head until he was very well within the walls of the secretariat. And then he only

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:53.480
[Guest]: realized when he first arrived in Delhi, clutching a letter, he was just a boy looking for a

00:40:53.480 --> 00:41:00.040
[Guest]: job. That was it. He was thinking of nothing like academic credentials or professional

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:05.000
[Guest]: qualifications. He was just looking for a way to survive. And this part of the story

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:10.600
[Guest]: is another part that's gone down in the legend that surrounds V.P. Menon, right? Because

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:15.800
[Guest]: we've heard of how he reaches Delhi and his pocket is picked. And he basically reaches

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:23.080
[Guest]: Delhi in the spring of 1914. And he's 21 years old by this point. And he arrives to find

00:41:23.080 --> 00:41:28.280
[Guest]: that the government has essentially packed its bags and gone off to Simla as it does

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:32.600
[Guest]: every year. But he wasn't to know that. So he was just basically told, please go back,

00:41:32.600 --> 00:41:37.240
[Guest]: catch another train and go to Simla. And he arrives at the station and finds his wallet

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:42.120
[Guest]: has been stolen. Now in legend, it's gone down that it was a kindly Sardarji who gave

00:41:42.120 --> 00:41:46.280
[Guest]: him the money. Actually, what happened was that it was a fellow Mallu who gave him the

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:50.920
[Guest]: money. And this fellow Mallu will play a huge role in his life later on, though he's not

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:55.800
[Guest]: to know that now. But he's given the money to go off to Simla. He arrives in Simla, goes

00:41:55.800 --> 00:42:00.600
[Guest]: to Gautam Castle, presents the letter and is told, boss, we don't have any openings.

00:42:01.240 --> 00:42:06.520
[Guest]: And he's dumbstruck because he was under the rather naive impression that if this gentleman

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:09.960
[Guest]: had given him a letter of recommendation, there must be a job. How can there not be

00:42:09.960 --> 00:42:14.920
[Guest]: a job? And he persists and he says, there must be something you can do. And these guys

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:19.640
[Guest]: say, okay, fine. There's this clerk who's gone off on vacation. He's gone for two months.

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:23.240
[Guest]: You're free to join for two months, but that's all we can give you. It's a temporary

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:28.360
[Guest]: job. If you want it, you can have it. And he takes it. And it's again, it's a life

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:33.800
[Guest]: changing moment for him because it's also a moment that speaks to me of a lot of desperation

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:38.360
[Guest]: because there is zero way that he can go back now with nothing. And he's heard about

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:42.360
[Guest]: government service. He doesn't know what it entails, but he's heard that once you

00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:46.680
[Guest]: get into government service, it can give you a good life and a stable life, which is what

00:42:46.680 --> 00:42:52.600
[Guest]: he's looking for. And at this point, he is just driven by questions of survival. How

00:42:52.600 --> 00:42:57.160
[Guest]: do you survive? How do you make money? How do you keep your stomach full? And he says,

00:42:57.160 --> 00:43:03.880
[Guest]: okay, fine. I'll take the job. And in those two months, he's also hunting for more permanent

00:43:03.880 --> 00:43:08.440
[Guest]: forms of employment. Nothing is coming along. And the directorate of statistics, which I

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:15.240
[Guest]: referred to earlier, that set up. And he thinks, what the hell? I will just put in a word.

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:21.640
[Guest]: I will apply directly to the registrar and see what he can do. And again, it's the same

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:28.680
[Guest]: sort of brazen devil-may-care attitude that supported him earlier. This is somebody who

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:33.640
[Guest]: never seemed to care that he had anything to lose. He always went at life like that.

00:43:33.640 --> 00:43:37.240
[Amit Varma]: He had nothing to lose. As Dylan once wrote, if you ain't got nothing, you got nothing

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:42.600
[Guest]: to lose. Absolutely. Which at every stage of his life, he ain't got nothing. So he was

00:43:42.600 --> 00:43:46.200
[Guest]: just going for it. And it's something that I really admired at the outset. You've got

00:43:46.200 --> 00:43:50.680
[Guest]: nothing. You've got no academic credentials. You're a temporary typist. And yet you have

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:54.760
[Guest]: the audacity to write a letter and say, look, there's a directorate that's opening up. It's

00:43:54.760 --> 00:44:01.400
[Guest]: going to need manpower. Here I am. What do you say? And this file actually still exists

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:06.440
[Guest]: in the National Archives. It's this really ancient, brittle file, but it has VP's first

00:44:06.440 --> 00:44:12.760
[Guest]: letter in 1914. And it has the registrar's reply as well, saying that we've considered

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:16.360
[Guest]: your application and you're good to go. And he's packing his bags to go from Simla to

00:44:16.360 --> 00:44:21.880
[Guest]: Delhi when the First World War breaks out. Yet again, a game-changing moment for VP.

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:25.800
[Guest]: Because once the war breaks out, officials are going back home. They're going to enlist

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:30.760
[Guest]: in the war. More spaces are opening up. So he's got a good chance of making this work

00:44:30.760 --> 00:44:36.760
[Guest]: for the first time. He's still not a confirmed employee of the Government of India. And this

00:44:36.760 --> 00:44:41.160
[Guest]: is something that's going to be true of his career for the next four years. He will not

00:44:41.160 --> 00:44:45.640
[Guest]: be a confirmed employee. He will be bobbing from department to department. He worked in

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:50.440
[Guest]: the Directorate of Statistics for a while. He would then go on to work as a clerk in

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:56.200
[Guest]: Lady Harding's Medical College Committee. He would do really temporary stuff, which

00:44:56.200 --> 00:45:01.560
[Guest]: sort of stopped gap employments, you know, one month, two months, six months. And this

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:08.120
[Guest]: was to continue until Edwin Montague became Secretary of State for India. And when Montague

00:45:08.120 --> 00:45:14.120
[Guest]: goes ahead and makes his famous August 20th declaration, which is essentially speaking

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:19.880
[Guest]: to the fact that one day, and that day is not specified right now, but one day, India

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:24.520
[Guest]: will have the right to self-governing institutions. And Montague himself is somebody who's creating

00:45:24.520 --> 00:45:29.960
[Guest]: a lot of waves for very different reasons in Whitehall, because Montague is very mercurial,

00:45:29.960 --> 00:45:35.880
[Guest]: very temperamental, also loves the limelight, as a certain Viceroy will decades later. But

00:45:35.880 --> 00:45:41.800
[Guest]: Montague is also rather radical in his outlook as far as the colony is concerned. He's somebody

00:45:41.800 --> 00:45:46.600
[Guest]: who feels that, look, if you're giving Indians a westernized form of education, if you're

00:45:46.600 --> 00:45:51.400
[Guest]: teaching them to think like us, they will think like us. Why will they not want independence

00:45:51.400 --> 00:45:58.440
[Guest]: at some point? And VPs heard Montague's speech on the radio, and he's completely startled

00:45:58.440 --> 00:46:03.480
[Guest]: by this. He's never heard this kind of speech before. And in his later years, when he's

00:46:03.480 --> 00:46:08.120
[Guest]: actually talking to Harry Hodgson about this, he says, Montague was somebody I thought was

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:12.440
[Guest]: a real visionary. And if he had been allowed to stay, he could have done wonderful things

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:17.320
[Guest]: at that point. We all know history didn't go quite that way. But anyway, Edwin Montague

00:46:17.320 --> 00:46:23.880
[Guest]: is coming out to India in the winter of 1917. And this is when the first sort of germs of

00:46:23.880 --> 00:46:29.320
[Guest]: the reforms branch are put together. So Montague essentially will need a roving sort of branch

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:34.440
[Guest]: to accompany him across the country as he's undertaking a tour. He's going to various

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:39.400
[Guest]: provinces, he's going to princely states to basically meet political leaders, princes,

00:46:39.400 --> 00:46:44.600
[Guest]: etc., get their opinions about the ideas that he's got for India. Accompanying him will

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:50.760
[Guest]: be a small team, typists, stenographers, clerks, and it will be headed by somebody called William

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:55.000
[Guest]: Maris. Now, this wasn't called the reforms branch at this point, it was called the emergency

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:59.880
[Guest]: branch. But essentially, it was what would become the reforms branch later. William Maris

00:46:59.880 --> 00:47:04.920
[Guest]: was technically India's first reforms commissioner, though that post hadn't been invented yet.

00:47:04.920 --> 00:47:11.800
[Guest]: Maris and Montague would not get on. But it was a moment that changed VP's career because

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:19.160
[Guest]: he has now gone from a miniscule salary to 120 rupees a month, plus 2 rupees for traveling

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:26.440
[Guest]: allowance. He is now for the first time exposed to what goes on behind making laws that can

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:32.920
[Guest]: potentially change history. And it's nothing as soul-stirring as he probably thought it

00:47:32.920 --> 00:47:38.680
[Guest]: was. It was essentially a lot of bickering and squabbling over redrafting sentences,

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:45.160
[Guest]: over changing the position of a clause. Should clause A be clause C instead? Does that give

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:50.840
[Guest]: this act more weight? It's stuff that can be mind-numbingly boring. And yet, because

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:55.960
[Guest]: it was being played out in front of him, he would eventually become Maris' go-to person,

00:47:55.960 --> 00:48:01.640
[Guest]: in the sense that he was primary typist that Maris would essentially have in the room to

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:07.720
[Guest]: basically take notes, redraft certain pages and phrases. So he was present when Maris

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:13.000
[Guest]: and Montague began squabbling, began arguing. And again, this is not something that's found

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:16.920
[Guest]: its way into his own official narrative of this. This is something that lived in his

00:48:16.920 --> 00:48:21.640
[Guest]: memory. And he spoke about this to Hudson years later after he'd quit government service.

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:26.360
[Guest]: And the fights between Maris and Montague actually come alive when VP talks about this.

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:31.560
[Guest]: You know, he's basically talking about two different people with two very different

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:38.200
[Guest]: perspectives on how this should go for India. Maris didn't agree with a lot of what Montague

00:48:38.200 --> 00:48:42.840
[Guest]: was saying. Maris had to shut up about it for so long that eventually it began to affect

00:48:42.840 --> 00:48:47.160
[Guest]: the working of the entire team because Maris would take to sulking and Montague would take

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:52.680
[Guest]: to being incredibly irritated and frustrated. And eventually, you know, dams of frustration

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:57.400
[Guest]: burst and there would be screaming matches. Montague would be thumping the table and telling

00:48:57.400 --> 00:49:01.720
[Guest]: Maris that he had been basically hired to do this particular job. And if he didn't want to do it,

00:49:01.720 --> 00:49:07.720
[Guest]: he could get out. And to all of this, VP was privy, right? So he's sitting there. He's now

00:49:08.360 --> 00:49:13.960
[Guest]: seeing actually what happens behind the scenes for the first time. He's exposed to high pressure

00:49:13.960 --> 00:49:22.200
[Guest]: situations, to huge egos, to how badly tempers can fray under pressure. He's also exposed to

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:29.320
[Guest]: the real boring aspect of reform. Not all reform is revolutionary. This is the kind of reform that

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:35.160
[Guest]: takes years to put together almost. That takes weeks of sleepless nights where you sit up and

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:42.520
[Guest]: you basically read the same thing over and over again until it reads better. And that, I think,

00:49:42.520 --> 00:49:49.160
[Guest]: impacted his career hugely because most of his career was built on knowledge that he gained

00:49:49.160 --> 00:49:53.240
[Guest]: firsthand. This wasn't knowledge that you could gain from a book. This wasn't knowledge that you

00:49:53.240 --> 00:49:58.360
[Guest]: could gain from sitting for any kind of exam. This was knowledge that you got only by being

00:49:58.360 --> 00:50:05.160
[Guest]: in the same room as the people making the laws, as people making history. And it involved a lot

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:11.080
[Guest]: of stuff that he had expected. He would always remember those moments as being very crucial to

00:50:11.080 --> 00:50:17.560
[Guest]: how he actually went about the business of making laws and making amendments to various laws because

00:50:17.560 --> 00:50:24.920
[Guest]: he watched Maris being unable to navigate as far as Montague was concerned. And he realized that,

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:29.320
[Guest]: you know what, sometimes you have to navigate through different personalities. You have to

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:35.720
[Guest]: be able to sort of slip and slide your way through until you get your point heard. It need not always

00:50:35.720 --> 00:50:40.200
[Guest]: involve a shouting match. It can, of course, sometimes under high pressure situations.

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:45.640
[Guest]: But he basically learned his art of diplomacy. And I don't say this lightly. I think he was the

00:50:45.640 --> 00:50:52.200
[Guest]: greatest internal diplomat that we've had as well, because he was navigating two different parties at

00:50:52.200 --> 00:50:57.640
[Guest]: one point in his life. He was navigating three different political interests and formulating

00:50:57.640 --> 00:51:02.600
[Guest]: two different countries at the end of his career, not to mention dealing with independent states.

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:10.760
[Guest]: So he received his training 100% on the job. And I think that is something that makes his story

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:17.000
[Guest]: unique. It makes his own career and his own life stand apart, because this was knowledge that he

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:21.000
[Amit Varma]: couldn't have gained from a book. In fact, you know, it struck me while reading your book,

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:25.160
[Amit Varma]: and I had a sense of this even before reading your book, because everyone sort of knows V.P.

00:51:25.160 --> 00:51:29.960
[Amit Varma]: Menon. And I'd read one of his books while prepping for one of my earlier episodes with

00:51:29.960 --> 00:51:34.680
[Amit Varma]: Srinath Raghavan. And it struck me totally that he is probably our greatest civil servant. I mean,

00:51:34.680 --> 00:51:39.240
[Amit Varma]: I can't even see how you would make a shortlist at all. I mean, he's just clearly the obvious

00:51:39.240 --> 00:51:43.960
[Amit Varma]: choice for all the remarkable things he did. And what's interesting in what your book brings out

00:51:43.960 --> 00:51:48.360
[Amit Varma]: is that his biography prepared him for it, that everything that was happening in his life

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:53.800
[Amit Varma]: was almost like an academy for what would happen in the 1940s at that crucial moment our nation

00:51:53.800 --> 00:51:58.760
[Amit Varma]: was born. For example, in 1914, you've quoted from a letter he's written to his brother where

00:51:58.760 --> 00:52:03.320
[Amit Varma]: he's saying, God has been very kind to me. I have been given my fair share of second and third

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:09.080
[Amit Varma]: chances. I will make this one work, stop quote. And then the Department of Statistics was very

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:13.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of interesting to me. He didn't stay there long. But what you've written about it, and again,

00:52:13.560 --> 00:52:18.520
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote your words, quote, the modern but dingy offices of the newly established directorate of

00:52:18.520 --> 00:52:23.560
[Amit Varma]: statistics embodied the Raj's passion for statistics and recorded information, the size

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:28.760
[Amit Varma]: and diversity of India in its population, its geography and agricultural produce made its

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:34.680
[Amit Varma]: imperative for its quote unquote masters to keep painstaking records of changes in demography,

00:52:34.680 --> 00:52:40.120
[Amit Varma]: crop production and prices, rainfall, industrial production, education, sanitation, mining and

00:52:40.120 --> 00:52:44.680
[Amit Varma]: transport. The directorate had been established in April 1914. With this ambitious goal in mind,

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:50.600
[Amit Varma]: the compilation of this information was probably as crashingly boring as it sounds. But to VP,

00:52:50.600 --> 00:52:56.040
[Amit Varma]: it was eye opening for the first time in his life. He was given a bird's eye view of the science of

00:52:56.040 --> 00:53:01.400
[Amit Varma]: India, stop quote. And what you referred to earlier, that you know, people often think of

00:53:01.400 --> 00:53:05.640
[Amit Varma]: the you know, if you're talking about the shaping of a nation, you think of grand speech, great

00:53:05.640 --> 00:53:11.800
[Amit Varma]: ideas, these are the high principles. But here is someone who 33 years before India actually

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:17.960
[Amit Varma]: becomes independent. Yeah, he's actually learning the country through statistics, through data,

00:53:17.960 --> 00:53:24.600
[Amit Varma]: through this mindless log of trying to figure it out, which sounds both to me fantastically boring

00:53:24.600 --> 00:53:29.720
[Amit Varma]: and incredibly inspiring. So that's a good note to take a quick commercial break while we figure

00:53:29.720 --> 00:53:36.280
[Amit Varma]: out which one it is. If you're listening to the scene in the unseen, it means you like listening

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:41.160
[Amit Varma]: to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case, I'd urge you to check out

00:53:41.160 --> 00:53:47.160
[Amit Varma]: Storytel, the sponsors of this episode. Storytel is an audiobook platform that has a massive range

00:53:47.160 --> 00:53:51.640
[Amit Varma]: of audiobooks from around the world. The international collection is stellar, but so is

